1. extractum. This implies some compulsion, but not necessarily physical force: cp. ‘contuberniis extracti' (15. 13, ²); ‘rure extractus in urbem ‘ (Hor. Sat. 1. 1, 11). The case is probably abl„ as in Horace (l. 1.); but in 6. 23, 5, the MS. text ‘extractum custodiae' is gene· rally accepted.

3. consternatione, ‘the tumultz’ cp. c. 63, 3; 13. 16, 6, etc. This noun ap- pears to originate with Livy. but the verb (cp. H. 3. 79, 3) is found earlier.

5. eastra primae legionis. Each legion had always more or less separate winter quarters, though the two here may have been in distinct portions of a com- mon enclosure. The context implies per- haps that his assailants followed him into this camp, and certainly that some of the legion, who are addressed as guilty by Germanicus, attacked him there.
